    "coverUrl": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/abhijitkhare-business/EasyFinanceLibrary/main/images/cover_news_issue_4.png",
    "content": "# Understanding ETFs: A Simple Guide to Exchange-Traded Funds\n\n## Easy Finance Newsletter | Issue #4 Feb 2026\n\nIf you want to invest in a basket of stocks but want the flexibility of trading them in real-time like individual shares, Exchange-Traded Funds (ETFs) are the answer.\n\nETFs have grown rapidly in popularity in India. Let's understand what they are and how they work.\n\n─────────────────────────\n🪙 What Is an ETF?\n\nAn Exchange-Traded Fund (ETF) is a collection of securities (like stocks or gold) that tracks an underlying index. \n\nFor example, a Nifty 50 ETF tracks the Nifty 50 index and holds the 50 largest companies in India in the same proportion as the index.\n\nThe key difference between an ETF and a mutual fund is that **ETFs trade on the stock exchange** like regular stocks. You can buy and sell them throughout the trading day at live market prices.\n\n─────────────────────────\n📊 ETFs vs. Mutual Funds: Key Differences\n\n• **Trading**: Mutual fund units are bought or sold at the end-of-day NAV. ETFs are traded live during market hours.\n• **Expense Ratio**: ETFs generally have much lower management fees (often below 0.2%) compared to active mutual funds.\n• **Demat Account**: You MUST have a demat and trading account to buy ETFs, whereas mutual funds can be bought without one.\n\n─────────────────────────\n🌱 Types of ETFs in India\n\n1. **Index ETFs**: Track Nifty 50, Sensex, Nifty Bank, etc.\n2. **Gold ETFs**: Track the domestic price of physical gold (each unit represents 1 gram of gold).\n3. **Sectoral/Theme ETFs**: Track specific sectors like IT, Pharma, or Public Sector Undertakings (PSUs).\n\n─────────────────────────\n📋 Key Takeaways\n• ETFs track an index and trade live on the stock exchange.\n• They offer low-cost diversification (very low expense ratios).\n• A demat and trading account is required to buy and sell ETFs.\n\n─────────────────────────\n🎯 Action Step\nIf you already have a demat account, search for Nifty 50 ETFs or Gold ETFs on your broker platform. Compare their expense ratios and trading volumes, and consider them for your passive investing portfolio."
